        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The Pentagon's homosexual harassment survey (editorial, March 28) should not be used to force soldiers to tolerate homosexuals, whose behavior the military considers illegal.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The Pentagon's homosexual harassment survey (editorial, March 28) should not be used to force soldiers to tolerate homosexuals, whose behavior the military considers illegal.</p>
        <p>The survey indicates some anti-homosexual harassment, but admits ''results cannot be statistically projected.'' Also, the number of incidents can't be determined. In most cases, entire close-knit units were surveyed. This dramatically increases the chance that responses reflect limited incidents.</p>
        <p>Military leaders should enforce existing laws to minimize harassment and violence. Meanwhile, the Clinton administration should scrap ''don't ask, don't tell'' (a policy I helped write as a member of a Pentagon task force) and unambiguously exclude homosexuals from military service.</p>
        <p>ROBERT L. MAGINNIS  Washington, March 28, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a senior director at the Family Research Council.</p>
      </block>
